    "answer_id" : 53451577,
    "question_id" : 2383265,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>The following code reads 4 bytes from <code>array</code> (a <code>byte[]</code>) at position <code>index</code> and returns a <code>int</code>.  I tried out most of the code from the other answers on Java 10 and some other variants I dreamed up.</p>\n\n<p>This code used the least amount of CPU time but allocates a <code>ByteBuffer</code> until Java 10's JIT gets rid of the allocation.</p>\n\n<pre><code>int result;\n\nresult = ByteBuffer.\n   wrap(array).\n   getInt(index);\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This code is the best performing code that does not allocate anything.  Unfortunately, it consumes 56% more CPU time compared to the above code.</p>\n\n<pre><code>int result;\nshort data0, data1, data2, data3;\n\ndata0  = (short) (array[index++] &amp; 0x00FF);\ndata1  = (short) (array[index++] &amp; 0x00FF);\ndata2  = (short) (array[index++] &amp; 0x00FF);\ndata3  = (short) (array[index++] &amp; 0x00FF);\nresult = (data0 &lt;&lt; 24) | (data1 &lt;&lt; 16) | (data2 &lt;&lt; 8) | data3;\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 6149312,
      "reputation" : 383,
      "user_id" : 4794229,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/128c8087cca274df148725f0d7d7bd65?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "mark_infinite",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4794229/mark-infinite"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1552830106,
    "creation_date" : 1552830106,
    "answer_id" : 55207695,
    "question_id" : 2383265,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Converting a 4-byte array into integer:</p>\n\n<pre><code>//Explictly declaring anInt=-4, byte-by-byte\nbyte[] anInt = {(byte)0xff,(byte)0xff,(byte)0xff,(byte)0xfc}; // Equals -4\n//And now you have a 4-byte array with an integer equaling -4...\n//Converting back to integer from 4-bytes...\nresult = (int) ( anInt[0]&lt;&lt;24 | ( (anInt[1]&lt;&lt;24)&gt;&gt;&gt;8 ) | ( (anInt[2]&lt;&lt;24)&gt;&gt;&gt;16) | ( (anInt[3]&lt;&lt;24)&gt;&gt;&gt;24) );\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 21768508,
      "reputation" : 51,
      "user_id" : 16071989,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b5604b11b7f36691957b1a0e49374dff?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Bluesillybeard2",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/16071989/bluesillybeard2"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1622325090,
    "creation_date" : 1622325090,
    "answer_id" : 67755986,
    "question_id" : 2383265,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Here is a simple solution that works for me:</p>\n<pre><code>int value = (a&amp;255)+((b&amp;255)&lt;&lt;8)+((c&amp;255)&lt;&lt;16)+((d&amp;255)&lt;&lt;24);\n</code></pre>\n<p>a is the least significant byte</p>\n<p>b is the second least significant byte</p>\n<p>c is the second most significant byte</p>\n<p>and d is the most significant byte</p>\n"
  } ],
